post_text:
GHS 8th grade students learning about Taxes in Math/Financial literacy...
Through a topic study of Income Tax Tables, students learned about the application of a compound inequality in a financial situation. Students watched a video (Where Do Your Tax Dollars Go?) and then discussed the programs that income taxes support. Students learned to read and analyze income tax tables for Single and Married Taxpayers, and also the historical trends of the highest income tax brackets since 1958. The overall goals were to learn about a real world application where compound inequalities show up, analyze tables and graphs and to learn how to use a spreadsheet to analyze data.
https://youtu.be/a7f6Z26w0yY

post_text:
GHS Community

I wish I had different news to share. We have not gotten clearance from the environmental company to open the school tomorrow. They are coming by Monday morning to see all of the progress and hopefully test the rooms that are complete. They are being extremely cautious and want to make sure that everything is as it should be. While I wish it was moving faster, I cannot fault them in their approach.
text:
GHS Community

I wish I had different news to share. We have not gotten clearance from the environmental company to open the school tomorrow. They are coming by Monday morning to see all of the progress and hopefully test the rooms that are complete. They are being extremely cautious and want to make sure that everything is as it should be. While I wish it was moving faster, I cannot fault them in their approach.

post_text:
GHS Community

Preliminary test results are in, and while we do not have them in our hands, RK Environmental has shared that there was a presence (mod potential) found in 19 of 59 rooms. A professional company will be brought in to begin the cleanup process as this is not a job our custodians are equipped to do.

School will be canceled until further notice. An update will follow tomorrow. I wish I could tell you the timeframe but it is dependent on cleanup and the advice of our environmental expert.

It was shared with us that this could not have been avoided. The combination of the summer humidity, the amount of rain, our roof project, and the uni-vent project caused an insurmountable amount of moisture to accumulate in our school.

Obviously the days will need to be made up. That info will be shared as soon as possible.

post_text:
GHS Community

Still no news. The testing companies are severely backed up and that is the hold up. We are waiting (not patiently) for the results. As soon as I know anything, we will send the info along. Until we get the clearance from RK Environmental, we will not be able to open.

post_text:
GHS Community

I understand the frustration concerning the school right now. We have absolutely no new information to share. The labs that do the work analyzing the samples are not open on the weekend.
Once we tested and took the approach of moving classes we ran the risk of running out of rooms.
Mold and mildew are in our homes, buildings we visit, and the outdoors. It is inescapable. I understand when it comes to our children that we want to be extra vigilant. That vigilance is the reason why we cannot guarantee when school will be open.

This morning, in completion of our Love of Reading Week Celebration and as a 20Time project, Ms. Lavalley's class invited all students with siblings born this school year to come and select a book from our Stork Stories collection. The students picked a book to take home to the future readers of GHS. They also received a letter addressed to the new baby and written by my first graders about why reading is important.

All of these students had or are about to have a sibling born. Our goal was to help start future readers of GHS on their journey to becoming readers!

Know that tomorrow, you are dropping off your most precious gifts to a school community that will take whatever measures possible to ensure their safety. We will be forever vigilant. But we will also do our best to help create children that know that they are valued, loved, and important. We need all of them. Every soul matters.

post_text:
I always loved Kurt Vonnegut's writing and remember this passage well. It is more important today than ever (passage edited for school).

From Scary Mommy:

Kurt Vonnegut, an American author best known for the novels Cat’s Cradle, Slaughterhouse-Five, and Breakfast of Champions, wrote some of the most important words I’ve ever read, in his novel God Bless You, Mr. Rosewater, or Pearls Before Swine, which was published in 1965:

Hello babies. Welcome to Earth. It’s hot in the summer and cold in the winter. It’s round and wet and crowded. On the outside, babies, you’ve got a hundred years here. There’s only one rule that I know of, babies-, you’ve got to be kind.'”

post_text: Something that truly resonates with me came from Crossfit competitor, Sam Dancer. He is a truly remarkable human being. In discussing goals and what he wants to achieve in life or where he will put his energies said, "You don't have to sacrifice the good things to do a good thing." His passion and conviction to his mission was clear. I believe at GHS we can be that also. We can do good things without sacrificing other things. We can be the best at innovating and still honor our traditions. We can focus on the creating the best possible individuals while also creating a sense of duty to others. We can be the best versions of ourselves.

post_text:
Greetings Green Families!
It is with tremendous joy and honor that I introduce myself as the new Principal of Green Hills School. I am elated to have the opportunity to serve in such a special, family-oriented community.
My personal values are founded in the belief that all children can learn, especially when given the tools and support to do so. Therefore, I will ensure that Green Hills continues to be a school that is student-centered and focused on meeting the individual needs of every single child in our care. I am also a strong proponent of collaboration and look forward to working alongside you in the most important and meaningful endeavor of our lives: raising and educating our children.
As we say “cheers” to a new beginning, I would like to invite you to a “meet and greet” prior to the start of the school year. Please join me in the Performing Arts room on Thursday, August 31st at 6:30 PM. Coffee, snacks, and great conversation will be served.
I look forward to meeting you!
Best,
Jennifer E. Thompson, Principal
Green Hills School
jthompson@greenhills.org
